text: Been struggling lately, Dani has been getting frustrated with her job to the point of talking about giving in her two weeks. She's a CDC worker and she just got a promotion to the lead of a couple of rooms. She's loved the job for two years, it puts her degree in early childhood education to use and she's a great worker. But the place has blatantly been taking advantage of her, always giving her hours she hates and tells them she hates because the rest of the building seems to have no issues with just calling out or demanding other hours or they'll quit and the management is weak, at best, with dealing with these kinds of things. She was hoping to switch to an earlier shift with the promotion, as none of the other leads close unless they want to and she found out last week she won't be changing at all. She works 9-6, but closing is more like 6:30 and it means she barely sees the older two boys... They're typically gone with me in the morning to their school center before she's awake and they go to bed at 8, so she gets maybe an hour and a half with them.
Sorry. Venting.
That’s rough, man
Sorry to hear that
When you just got a promotion is the best time to look for a new job
I'm sorry DM, my parents are divorced and my dad always taught out of state so I know how hard that is. Don't feel bad about venting, we're here for you
^I've never been in a full working environment but what Jason said makes sense
Looking for a job while jobless is stressful but looking while employed is hopeful and other employers are much more interested
Having options doesn't suck. It sounds like her job is taking advantage and she is in a position to go somewhere that won't

Yeah, she said yesterday that she's thinking about just submitting her two weeks and I told her to start looking now. Only wrench in the plan is that I am up for orders so we're kinda not sure where we're going to be in the next year or so.
That's my thinking, too, Jason

My dad worked his ass off. He chased the next promotion constantly and moved us from town to town and state to state climbing the ladder, and was pretty successful at it in that regard. He also didn't see a single baseball game I played, nor had time for any hobbies or interests. And then he got a brain tumor and died before he could retire and enjoy any of it.
There's a finite amount of my life I'm willing to put into my career as a result of that.

That said, it's easy for me to say that. I've been fairly successful in my job, and I'm at the point where I have a relatively relaxed work position that pays me well enough that I can afford to have that attitude.
I understand a lot of this

My dad worked nights at a job he hated to support our family. It made him an angry man to live with and I never liked my dad, growing up. Luckily, he retired early and while it wasn't the best financial idea, my mom and him are still stable and he's a much better grandfather than he was a father, in terms of social situations.
I had a similar story, <@U4V5EHQ2G>. My dad was a workaholic who was always traveling and rarely home, and he missed most of my events (though he did try to get to a few).

and I'm in a similar position to you work wise today. That said, my kids can't appreciate (and I don't expect them to) that I'd spent more time with them by the time they were 2 than my dad did when I was 18.

Yeah, my kids do a ton more and just get a ton more than I did at their age. Dani and I constantly talk about how we NEVER had the amount of toys, books or even clothes that those three little monsters have :smile:
They're also much more traveled than I was until I joined the military, let alone became an adult. My oldest had been on like five planes and visited 6 or 7 states before he was 1
Oh I had stuff, but the stuff was easy for my folks (also I was the youngest of 5 so I had all the hand-me-downs)

The trade-off being that I didn't see my oldest son for most of his first year of life, then missed two chunks of his life and one of Alex's. I wasn't supposed to be home for Nick's birth, but (ironically) getting sick had me med-vac'd in time for that
Silver lining and all that.

<@U3L7A68JC> I had stuff as a kid, wasn't trying to say like I was super wanting. But my kids just have a TON of stuff O.o We also haven't gotten rid of much because of how close in age all three kids are. Eight, six and three, there's always been hand-me-down clothes, toys, etc.
We've moved so often across country in their first 10 years of life which naturally kept the clutter down to a minimum, honestly.
Our next move, I'm purging the hell out of stuff. I still have clothes from when I was 22 and needless to say, I am not the same size. Or shape.
I always thought it was wierd on movies and TV when people went into old attics filled with stuff. People lived in the same house for more than 18 months? Weird.
I lived in two houses my entire life until I was 19.
Me too, <@U6YMA7NAV>

My Aunt Dorothy lived in her house for...50+ years and she had a whole third floor attic, basically. Needless to say her place became a collection point of 'stuff' from the extended family. After she died it too weeks to go through it all.

I’m running it because I’m maxed out on shuffle effects and fetches, but the average deck still shouldn’t play it.

Most times player treat Brainstorm like a more difficult to play [[reach through mists]]
